<br>
But, exactly how?<br>
<br>
Here is what I know:<br>
A1&gt; If a non-charmed pet has the most aggro, and there is no PC in melee range, the mob will attack the non-charmed pet.<br>
<br>
A2&gt; If a non-charmed pet has the most aggro, and a PC is in melee range, the mob will attack the highest aggro PC in melee range.<br>
<br>
A3&gt; Uncertain: If a PC successfully uses /taunt on an NPC, where there is an uncharmed pet that has the most aggro, the PC will gain the pets aggro.<br>
<br>
A4&gt; Uncertain: If a Pet successfully uses /taunt on an NPC, where there is a PC or another Pet that has the most aggro, the pet gains the PC's aggro.<br>
<br>
B1&gt; If there are fewer than 5 things (1 to 4) on a mobs aggro list, charmed pets behave like non-charmed pets aggro wise.<br>
<br>
B1 Clarification&gt; Both PCs and Pets (and maybe NPCs) count towards this limit.  So, if a PC makes their pet attack a mob, that is 2 things (both the pet and PC have aggro).  The charmed pet and the PC controlling the pet count as 2 of the 4 things, leaving at most 2 other aggro sources before things get wierd.<br>
<br>
B2&gt; If a charmed pet has the most aggro, and there are more than 4 things on the mobs aggro list, the mob will attack the most aggro PC, ignoring proximity.<br>
<br>
B3&gt; Uncertain: If a PC successfully uses /taunt on an NPC, where there is a charmed pet that has the most aggro, the PC will gain the pets aggro.<br>
<br>
B4&gt; Uncertain: Charmed pets /taunt ability.<br>
<br>
What I'm wondering about is how much do charmed pets and uncharmed pets aid in holding aggro.<br>
<br>
I do know how it worked before the charmed pet changes:<br>
<br>
X1&gt; If a Charmed pet has the most hate, then the highest aggro PC in melee range would be attacked.  Failing that, the pet would be attacked.<br>
<br>
X2&gt; If a PC used /taunt, they would gain all the aggro of the charmed pet.<br>
<br>
X2 was empirically tested in taking out BoT tower bosses.  A single charmed pet was used for initial engagement, tanks ran up periodically and tapped /taunt.  Wizards chain nuked without drawing aggro.  When charm broke, the tanks where summoned (not the wizards or the enchanter), stuns/mez where used to control the insane pet, and recovery was executed.<br>
<br>
I think if I'm right, the use of charmed pets on bosses should allow a warrior to bootstrap their aggro as fast as a SK or Paladin could.<br>
